Your task is to write a Jest test case that exposes a specific mutation in a JavaScript/TypeScript project.

MUTATION DETAILS
The mutation affects the following file:
throughs/take.js
Here is the full content of that file (shown with a <PLACEHOLDER> marker):
'use strict'

//read a number of items and then stop.
module.exports = function take (test, opts) {
  opts = opts || {}
  var last = opts.last || false // whether the first item for which !test(item) should still pass
  var ended = false
  if('number' === typeof test) {
    last = true
    var n = test; test = function () {
      return --n
    }
  }

  return function (read) {

    function terminate (cb) {
      read(true, function (err) {
           last = false; cb(true)

      })
    }

    return function (end, cb) {
      if(ended && !end) last ? terminate(cb) : cb(ended)
      else if(ended = end) read(ended, cb)
      else
        <PLACEHOLDER>
          }
          else if(!test(data)) {
            ended = true
            last ? cb(null, data) : terminate(cb)
          }
          else
            cb(null, data)
        })
    }
  }
}

In the original code, <PLACEHOLDER> has the value:

-             if(ended = ended || end) {
-               //last ? terminate(cb) :
-               cb(ended)
-             }
In the mutated code, <PLACEHOLDER> has the value:

+             if(ended = ended || end) {}


YOUR TASK
Write one Jest test file that:
    1. Passes when run against the original code.
    2. Fails when run against the mutated code.
    3. Tests the behavior of the mutated file in a way that reliably detects the mutation.
The test will be saved at the following path, relative to this test-generation project’s root:
llm-cache/anthropic_claude-sonnet-4.6/temp_0.5/withoutTests/cached/artifacts/pull-stream/attempt_1/pending_category/mutant-e7b88d9/testCase.test.ts

ALLOWED LIBRARIES
You may use:
    1. Any built-in Node.js modules (e.g., fs, path, crypto, etc.).

You may not use any other third-party libraries.

Looking at the mutation, the original code calls `cb(ended)` when an error/end condition is detected during a read, but the mutated code has an empty block `{}` instead, meaning `cb` is never called. This would cause the stream to hang without calling the callback.

Let me analyze the flow:
- The `take` through reads items and stops after a condition
- When `read` is called and returns an error or end, the original code calls `cb(ended)` to propagate that
- The mutation removes this `cb(ended)` call, so the callback is never invoked

I need to write a test that:
1. Creates a pull-stream pipeline using `take`
2. Exercises the code path where `read` returns an error/end condition
3. Verifies that the callback is actually called

```typescript
import take from "../../../../../../../../../../../subject_repositories/pull-stream/throughs/take.js";

describe("take through - callback invocation on end/error", () => {
  it("should call the callback when the source stream ends during a read", (done) => {
    // Create a take that allows up to 10 items (more than source has)
    const takeThrough = take(10);

    // Create a source that ends immediately (has 0 items)
    const source = (end: any, cb: Function) => {
      if (end) {
        cb(end);
        return;
      }
      // Immediately signal end of stream
      cb(true);
    };

    const through = takeThrough(source);

    // Read from the through - source ends immediately
    // This should trigger the path where read returns end=true
    // and the through should call cb(true) to signal end
    through(false, (end: any, data: any) => {
      // The callback should be called with end=true
      expect(end).toBe(true);
      done();
    });
  });
});
```

Wait, let me re-read the code more carefully. The mutation is in the `else` branch of `read(null, function(err, data) {...})`. When `err` is truthy (or `end` is truthy from the read), the original calls `cb(ended)` but the mutation doesn't call `cb` at all.

```typescript
import take from "../../../../../../../../../../../subject_repositories/pull-stream/throughs/take.js";

describe("take through - propagates end signal from source", () => {
  it("should call the callback when source signals end during read", (done) => {
    const takeThrough = take(10); // take up to 10 items

    // Source that ends after 2 items
    let count = 0;
    const source = (end: any, cb: Function) => {
      if (end) {
        cb(end);
        return;
      }
      count++;
      if (count > 2) {
        cb(true); // signal end
      } else {
        cb(null, count);
      }
    };

    const through = takeThrough(source);
    const results: number[] = [];

    function drain() {
      through(false, (end: any, data: any) => {
        if (end) {
          expect(results).toEqual([1, 2]);
          done();
          return;
        }
        results.push(data);
        drain();
      });
    }

    drain();
  });
});
```

